The paper deals with distributed computing and population protocols, which are typically studied in the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) and Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-categories. The paper also discusses the properties of predicates that can be stably computed, which falls under the scope of Information Theory (cs.IT) and Learning (cs.LG). Finally, the paper's focus on symmetry and parallelism could also be relevant to the Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-category.
